      "type": "answer",
      "text": "Cheat sheets solve one problem: **\"I know what to do but can't remember the exact syntax.\"**\n\n**What they do for learners:**\n- Save 10+ hours/donth Googling the same commands\n- Interview prep — quick reference before technical calls\n- On-the-job — paste commands instead of reading docs\n- Reinforce memory through repetition\n\n**What you can promise per track:**\n\n| Track | What the cheat sheet covers |\n|---|---|\n| **Web Dev** | HTML/CSS/JS syntax, flexbox grid, fetch API, ES6 |\n| **React** | Hooks, props, state, routing, component patterns |\n| **Node.js** | Express routes, middleware, npm commands, file ops |\n| **Python** | Syntax, pip, virtual envs, common libraries |\n| **DevOps** | Docker, Docker Compose, CI/CD pipelines, SSH |\n| **Cloud** | AWS/Azure/GCP CLI, IAM, S3, deployment commands |\n| **Git** | Branching, merging, rebasing, conflict resolution |\n| **SQL** | Joins, indexes, queries, PostgreSQL/MySQL specifics |\n| **AI/ML** | Python data libs, model training, API calls |\n\n**The promise:**\n> \"One page per topic. No fluff. Commands you'll actually use in production.\"\n\nThat's your value proposition. People don't buy cheat sheets for theory — they buy them to stop wasting time.",
      "timestamp": 1782283616506
    },
    {
