they need (quick reference for technical tasks) and selling it to others who have the same need.\n\nThe revealing part is that the AKcloud site itself is a cheat sheet of sorts - it's a landing page for a technical consultancy, and the cheat sheets they want to sell are extensions of the same knowledge they're using to build the business.\n\nAlso, the fact that they asked about \"remote into the site\" and \"manually make changes\" shows they want control and understanding, not just delegation.\n\nThe pattern across all scenarios:\n1. They have a vision (AKcloud, sovereign cloud, technical consultancy)\n2. They hit technical barriers (Odoo cache, CSS animations, Netlify credits)\n3. They ask me to fix it\n4. They want to understand it (but struggle with retention)\n5. They're looking for sustainable solutions (cheat sheets, CLI commands)\n\nThe cheat sheet idea is actually the most self-aware thing they've done - they're building the exact product they need.",
