      "text": "I can see that commits from `fe7ec8b` back to `695e29f` have \"opprah-maker\" as the author. The ones before that have either \"Andie Kobbie\" or \"opprah-maker\". Let me rewrite the history for the commits that have \"opprah-maker\" as the author.\n\nI'll use `git rebase -i` to edit the commits. The earliest commit with \"opprah-maker\" that I need to change is `695e29f`. So I need to rebase from the commit before that, which is `0121da9`.\n\nActually, let me think about this more carefully. The user said \"the last several ones\". Looking at the list:\n- fe7ec8b - opprah-maker\n- 79553ff - opprah-maker\n- 4a67961 - opprah-maker\n- d54585f - opprah-maker\n- 5813d0e - opprah-maker\n- 695e29f - opprah-maker\n- 0121da9 - Andie Kobbie (this one is fine)\n- 0ba3e5b - Andie Kobbie (this one is fine)\n- 9e86af7 - Andie Kobbie (this one is fine)\n- 5c61ba1 - opprah-maker\n\nSo I need to change commits from fe7ec8b down to 695e29f (6 commits). The parent of 695e29f is 0121da9.\n\nI'll use `git rebase -i 0121da9` and then edit each commit to change the author.\n\nActually, there's a simpler way - I can use `git filter-branch` or `git rebase` with the `--exec` option to amend the author on all commits in the range.\n\nLet me use `git rebase -i` and mark each commit as \"edit\", then amend the author.\n\nActually, the simplest approach is to use `git rebase -i` and for each commit, use `git commit --amend --author=\"andiekobbie <andiekobbietks@outlook.com>\"`.\n\nBut this is complex with interactive rebase. Let me use a different approach - `git filter-branch` with `--env-filter` to change the author.\n\nWait, `git filter-branch` is deprecated. Let me use `git rebase -i` with `--exec` to amend each commit.\n\nActually, the simplest approach is:\n1. `git rebase -i 0121da9` (the commit before the first opprah-maker commit)\n2. Mark all 6 commits as \"edit\"\n3. For each, run `git commit --amend --author=\"andiekobbie <andiekobbietks@outlook.com>\"` and continue\n\nBut this requires interactive input. Let me use a non-interactive approach instead.\n\nI can use `git rebase --exec` to run a command on each commit:\n\n```\ngit rebase 0121da9 --exec 'git commit --amend --author=\"andiekobbie <andiekobbietks@outlook.com>\" --no-edit'\n```\n\nThis will replay each commit and amend it with the new author. Let me try this.",
