      "type": "thought",
      "text": "The user is showing me their GitHub repository page and pointing out that the README has detailed information about their infrastructure - environment variables, function paths, authentication details, etc. They're asking if this basically gives a bad actor a roadmap to attack their infrastructure.\n\nLet me look at what's exposed:\n\n1. Function paths and their purposes\n2. Environment variable names (though not values)\n3. Authentication details (Basic auth for get-waitlist, \"None (add later)\" for submit-booking)\n4. Odoo integration details\n5. Admin panel path\n6. Security headers configuration\n\nThe user is right to be concerned. While the README doesn't contain actual secrets (API keys, passwords), it does provide an attacker with:\n- A map of all endpoints\n- Which ones have no auth\n- What the admin panel is and how to access it\n- The tech stack and potential vulnerabilities\n\nThis is essentially a penetration testing guide for their own site.\n\nI should advise them to:\n1. Remove sensitive details from the README\n2. Keep it minimal - just the high-level description\n3. Move detailed docs to a private repo or local file\n4. Add auth to all functions that need it",
